column12: HYDROCARBON DECOMPOSITION CATALYST, PROCESS FOR OBTAINING SAID CATALYST, AND A PROCESS FOR OBTAINING HYDROGEN AND SYNGAS EMPLOYING SAID CATALYST
column13: A process for the production of catalysts useful for hydrocarbon decomposition comprising the stages of : a) -f orming a mixed urea solution comprising soluble salts of metal ion selected from the group consisting in: a group I transition divalent metal (Me (II) ) selected between Co, Ni, Cu, and Zn; Al (III), and Mn(II), at pH between 3 and 6, b) -ageing the mixed solution containing urea-Me(II)- magnesium ( II ) -aluminum ( III ) at a temperature between 70 and 100° C; c) - precipitating from the aged solution a double laminar hydroxide (HDL) consisting of said divalent metal (Me (II) ), magnesium, and aluminum, in order to form a catalyst precursor, d) -activating the catalyst precursor obtained in stage c) by reduction in an atmosphere containing hydrogen at atmospheric pressure, and at a temperature between 600 and 750° C. Catalysts obtained by said process, and a hydrogen and syngas production process employing said catalysts are also disclosed.

column12: Dual-action electro-wound membranes for water treatment (Machine-translation by Google Translate, not legally binding)
column13: Double action electrohilated membranes for water treatment. The present invention consists of a process for the manufacture of active membranes based on submicrometric fibers that combine an antimicrobial action with the retention capacity of apolar contaminants in aqueous solution. The membranes are produced by an electrospinning process in aqueous solution from mixtures of a water-soluble polyacid and a polyalcohol which are stabilized by a curing process and post-functionalized by the incorporation of dendrimers with amino terminus by a process of grafted can help from a coupling agent. The application of the material is the production of membranes or components of multilayer membranes for water treatment with antimicrobial action and with capacity to retain apolar contaminants. (Machine-translation by Google Translate, not legally binding)
